  "RTL-SDR": "RTL-SDR",
  "RTL-SDR Setup": "RTL-SDR Setup",
  "Do you already own an RTL-SDR receiver?": "Do you already own an RTL-SDR receiver?",
  "What is RTL-SDR?": "What is RTL-SDR?",
  "RTL-SDR setup — no receiver body": "RTL-SDR turns a low-cost USB radio dongle into a marine AIS receiver.\n\nWhy is it useful?\n• Receive live vessel positions near your observation point\n• Works offline when Internet AIS is unavailable\n• Enables Hybrid mode (Internet + local reception)\n\nRecommended hardware:\n• RTL-SDR Blog V4 (recommended)\n• Nooelec SMArt / NESDR\n• Airspy (future support)\n\nApproximate price: €30–€50 for the dongle; add €20–€80 for a VHF antenna.\n\nTypical antenna: outdoor VHF marine antenna mounted as high as practical, with clear line of sight toward open water.",
  "Continue using Internet AIS only": "Continue using Internet AIS only",
  "Operating System": "Operating System",
  "Windows": "Windows",
  "Linux": "Linux",
  "Setup guide": "Setup guide",
  "RTL-SDR setup guide — Windows": "1. Install the RTL-SDR USB driver (Zadig: WinUSB for the RTL2832 device).\n2. Install the RTL-SDR tools package (rtl-sdr).\n3. Install AIS-Catcher and place the executable where Project X expects it.\n4. Connect the RTL-SDR receiver and antenna.\n5. Click Detect RTL device, then Start AIS-Catcher, then run the reception test.",
  "RTL-SDR setup guide — Linux": "1. Install packages: rtl-sdr, librtlsdr-dev (distribution packages).\n2. Blacklist the DVB-T kernel module if it grabs the device: create /etc/modprobe.d/rtl-sdr.conf with blacklist dvb_usb_rtl28xxu.\n3. Add udev rules so your user can access the device without root.\n4. Verify detection with rtl_test -t.\n5. Install AIS-Catcher, connect the receiver, then test from this wizard.",
